): eyeColor is the optic light: amber-optic, red-sensor, blue-light, white-lens, green-cathode. hairColor and skinColor describe the chassis: rusted-iron, polished-chrome, tarnished-brass, dented-plasteel, matte-black alloy.(cranialStructure): Examples: domed sensor-housing, armored rectangular-headcase, skeletal jaw-actuator, functional humanoid-headcase, spherical optic-mount.(facialFeatures): Possible features include single glowing-optic, smooth metallic-faceplate, external audio-receptors, vocalizer grille, articulated jaw-plate.

Part 5: TerransA Xenological Addendum: Species VariationCore Trait: Terrans are the galactic baseline, defined not by biology but by a psychological addiction to narrative. They must be the hero, the villain, or the victim of a grand story. In an age with no more stories, their societal structure has fractured into distinct castes, each defined by their relationship to the dead heroic age.Polymorphism (Socio-Economic Castes):The Elite (Star Barons): The architects of the system's decay. They live in pristine, sterile environments like Geneva Prime or the luxury arcologies of Luna, utterly detached from the consequences of their greed. Their psychology is one of sociopathic control, viewing worlds as assets and people as line items. They are the untouchable villains of the noir narrative, their hands clean because they paid others to do the killing.The Government (Directorate Agents): The enforcers of the rigged game. They are the military, the bureaucrats, and the lawmen who serve the Star Barons' system. They operate from a place of cold, clinical pragmatism, their morality eroded by the demands of maintaining a corrupt status quo. They are the compromised cops and cynical officials of the noir world, men like Marshal Brody who know the truth is a luxury the system cannot afford.The Masses (The Common Man): The teeming, forgotten majority who inhabit the industrial sacrifice zones like Baikonur or the lawless frontiers of the Belt. They are the prospectors, pirates, and grease monkeys whose lives are spent in the shadow of the Elite's ambition. Their psychology is one of grim, cynical survival. They are the bartenders, the informants, and the everyday victims who know the game is rigged because they lose it every single day.The Exiles (Ignition City): The ghosts of the heroic age. Dumped on Mars and left to rot, they are the living embodiment of "Narrative Deprivation." Their skills are obsolete, their glory is a fading memory, and their heroism has curdled into either drunken self-pity or fanatical violence. They are the ultimate noir protagonists: men and women with a code, trapped in a world that has rendered it meaningless.Nomenclature (Classic, Two-part, Anglo-American Pulp/Noir Inspired)Dash CorriganSally StarlightJet PowersBrick SamsonGage RileyApparel (Divided by Caste, Reflecting a Decaying Dream)The Elite (Star-Baron): Sharp, minimalist business suits of self-cleaning, high-tech fabric; long, severe coats with high collars; clothing as a sterile, corporate uniform devoid of personal expression.The Government (Directorate): Utilitarian, high-collared, grey or black uniforms; armored blast-vests over practical shipsuits; heavy, mag-locked combat boots; clothing as an instrument of imposing, faceless authority.The Common Man (The Masses): Worn, patched synth-leather dusters; greasy, stained mechanic's coveralls; heavy, steel-toed work boots; clothing as a record of a hard-lived, practical life.The Exiles (Ignition City): A cracked, silver flight-suit with synth-leather patches over the knees; a once-pristine uniform tunic with a ray-gun burn on the collar; a fishbowl helmet with a spiderweb of cracks sealed with yellowing adhesive; a jetpack held together with scavenged parts and hope; a hero's costume worn until it became a beggar's rags.System Directive: S-Expression ProtocolGeneric Human Protocol(eyeColor hairColor skinColor): eyeColor: steel-grey, ice-blue, whiskey-brown, tired-green, cynical-hazel. hairColor: jet-black, silver-grey, dishwater-blonde, fiery-red, salt-and-pepper. skinColor: weathered-tan, sallow-pale, ruddy-complexion, fair-skinned, olive-toned.(hairStyle): Examples: slicked-back with pomade, short military-crew-cut, thinning comb-over, messy unkempt-shock, neat professional-bob.(facialFeatures): Possible features include broken nose, tired bloodshot-eyes, thin cynical-lips, a three-day-stubble, haggard cheekbones.(height build): Examples: tall lanky, average stocky, short wiry, tall heavy-set, average lean.(Attire): Examples: worn synth-leather duster, greasy mechanic-coveralls, cheap ill-fitting-suit, patched work-shirt, heavy steel-toed-boots.Caste-Specific S-Expression ModificationsThe Elite (Star-Baron)(facialFeatures): Possible features include soft unlined-skin, cold piercing-gaze, thin predatory-lips, manicured nails, perfectly capped-teeth.(Attire): Examples: immaculate business-suit, severe high-collar-coat, sterile corporate-uniform, expensive tailored-slacks, self-cleaning fabric-shirt.(personality): Possible traits include cold, calculating, sociopathic, arrogant, detached.The Government (Directorate)(facialFeatures): Possible features include hard impassive-face, square jaw, observant narrowed-eyes, regulation shave, thin scar on cheek.(Attire): Examples: utilitarian grey-uniform, armored blast-vest, practical shipsuit, heavy mag-locked-boots, formal dress-uniform.(personality): Possible traits include pragmatic, cynical, detached, authoritarian, world-weary.The Masses (Common Man)(facialFeatures): Possible features include tired bloodshot-eyes, broken nose, calloused hands, grease under-fingernails, worried frown-lines.(Attire): Examples: patched synth-leather-duster, greasy mechanic-coveralls, faded plaid-shirt, worn-out work-boots, oil-stained-trousers.(personality): Possible traits include cynical, resilient, fatalistic, suspicious, pragmatic.The Exiles (Ignition City)(facialFeatures): Possible features include puffy face from-alcohol, burst capillaries, haunted distant-gaze, trembling hands, faded heroic-jawline.(Attire): Examples: cracked silver-jumpsuit with synth-leather patches, faded red-tunic with raygun-burns, fishbowl helmet sealed with adhesive, tarnished jetpack held with mismatched-straps, once-white uniform now-grey-and-stained.(personality): Possible traits include nostalgic, bitter, fanatical, broken, self-pitying.

This is the true beginning of the story of Jones's last days.

Step 1: Following the Heart (And Finding a Wall)
It started with a worry that had curdled into fear. Jones had watched Cody, the boy he’d practically raised, get swallowed whole by Lance Sterling’s Pioneer’s Vigil. The hero worship that had once been directed at him was now aimed at a zealot. It was a personal failure, and Jones felt its weight. Before turning to the city’s shadows, he turned to his last true friend: Brick Samson.
He went to the Star Bar, not as an investigator, but as a friend asking for help. The place was quiet. He slid the old, faded photograph across the worn bar top. The image of the two of them, younger, invincible, a lifetime ago. He pointed to the note he’d written on the back: "Watch out for the Kid."
"He's in trouble, Brick," Jones said, his voice low. "Sterling's got his hooks in him. Gage Riley is his shadow. They're planning something. I need your help to pull him out before it's too late."
Brick looked at the photo, then at the door, then at the bottle in his hand. The fear in his eyes was stark, cutting through the usual alcoholic haze. He pushed the photo back across the bar. "Leave it alone, Johnny," he said, his voice barely a whisper. "This is different. Sterling and his boys... they're not a joke anymore. You cross them, you end up in a cryo-tube in Ur-Ea's morgue. I can't. I'm just a bartender."
Jones looked at his friend, the man who had flown into the heart of a nebula with him on a dare, and saw a stranger. He picked up the photograph, the promise on the back now a testament to a friendship that had just died. He was alone. If he was going to uncover what Sterling was planning and save the kid, he'd have to do it himself. He put the photo in his pocket and walked out, leaving Brick to his fear and his bottle.
The Clue Left Behind (Found on Jones's body): An Old Photograph. It shows a younger Jones and Brick Samson. On the back, a note: "Brick - Remember the promise we made. Watch out for the Kid." This is the key to the entire investigation. It's not just a memento; it's the record of a plea for help. It identifies the first person Jones turned to, and the first person who turned their back on him. It points to Brick not just as a source of information, but as the first domino to fall in a story of betrayal.

Step 2: Following the Tech
Jones knew a war, even a suicidal one, needed weapons. Not just blasters, but real hardware. The kind you can’t buy over a counter. There was only one place in the city to get that kind of off-the-books, military-grade tech: Pavel’s chop shop in the Undercrawl.
Jones went to see the Mole Man. Pavel, terrified but pragmatic, would sell to anyone. Jones didn’t make a scene. He just asked what kind of components Gage Riley had been buying. For a handful of credits, Pavel showed him. It was heavy stuff—shielding components, power conduits, navigational systems. All of it scavenged, all of it dangerous. To have a tangible piece of evidence, Jones purchased a small, representative item from the same lot: a non-standard power cell, already showing signs of overload from Pavel’s crude tests.
The Clue Left Behind: A Burned-Out Power Cell. It’s non-standard, military-grade, and clearly overloaded. On its casing is the faint, almost invisible maker's mark of Pavel's chop shop, a stylized mole's claw inside a cog. This is the first thread. It leads directly to the source.
Of course. Here is the next step in the timeline, detailing Jones's logical progression and the next clue he uncovers.

Step 3: Following the Logic
Jones had the list of parts. Shielding, high-yield power conduits, navigational arrays. This was more than a stockpile; it was a project. But what was it for? He wasn't a theoretical physicist, but he knew one. The only mind in the city brilliant enough to see the design behind the components and paranoid enough to understand its implications was Lugal.
Navigating the treacherous junk fields to the crashed Zetan saucer was a risk, but Jones was methodical. He approached the fortified scrap heap and was granted access. Inside the shielded cockpit, surrounded by the quiet hum of defensive systems, Jones presented his findings to the reclusive Gray. He showed him the list of scavenged Terran tech.
Lugal, his mind a precision instrument, saw the pattern immediately. This wasn't just a power source for a ship. The specific combination of energy shielding and navigational hardware pointed to something far more dangerous. It was a crude, brutalist attempt to replicate a Zetan stealth field generator—a "cloaking device." Lugal explained it would be dangerously unstable, a ticking bomb that could tear a hole in reality. To give Jones the proof he needed, and a warning, Lugal handed him a small data crystal containing the theoretical specifications, showing how the scavenged Terran parts were being dangerously jury-rigged to a Zetan design concept.
The Clue Left Behind: A small, damaged Zetan Data Crystal. To make the complex theory understandable, it's wrapped in a piece of flimsiplast. On the flimsiplast is a hand-drawn diagram showing the crystal's schematics interfacing with a Terran power system, with the name "Lugal" scribbled next to a note on energy fluctuation. The clue identifies not just the technology but the expert who can explain it.
Excellent. The investigation continues, following the cold, hard logic of resources.

Step 4: Following the Resources
Jones now knew what they were building. The next question was where. A project of that magnitude—an unstable, jury-rigged cloaking field—would generate a catastrophic amount of heat. It would need a massive, dedicated cooling system. In Ignition City, industrial-grade coolant means one thing: water. And all water flows from one place.
His investigation led him to the rusted, skeletal frame of the Discovery One, the city's water condenser station. He confronted the facility's sole operator, Hemi. The Gill-Man was terrified. Creatures like Hemi survive by being invisible, by not making waves. But Gage Riley, Sterling's blunt instrument, had already paid him a visit. Under Jones's quiet, persistent questioning, Hemi's resolve crumbled.
He confessed he'd been strong-armed by Riley into diverting a massive quantity of purified water, far more than anyone could ever drink. It was pumped out under the designation "hyper-coolant." Hemi, fearing for his life, had rerouted the shipment to a disused reclamation valve at the edge of the scrap fields, a place no one ever goes. A place near the old, derelict landmark everyone mistakes for a natural mesa. Jones, ever the pragmatist, took the physical record of the transaction.
The Clue Left Behind: A Water Ration Chit. On the back, an unusual debit is noted for a massive quantity of purified water, enough for a hundred men for a month. Next to the debit, a hastily scrawled note reads: "HYPER-COOLANT." This clue connects the conspiracy's resources to a specific, remote location.
Understood. The investigation is now closing in. Jones has the what and the where. Now he needs the why and the who.

Step 5: Following the Money
A massive, secret project requires more than parts and water. It requires a neutral ground for deals, a place to move money and components without the Marshal's prying eyes. Jones knew there was only one establishment in the city that guaranteed that level of shielded privacy: Seti's gambling den, The Cold Hand.
Jones walked into the quiet, magnetically shielded cargo hold of The Vorga. He didn't go to the sabacc tables. He went straight to Seti. The old Saurian pirate, cold and reptilian, recognized Jones not as a hero, but as a former adversary from a forgotten skirmish in the Belt. There was a grudging respect between them. Jones didn't make accusations; he made a transaction. He laid down a stack of credits and asked a simple question: had Gage Riley been renting his back rooms?
Seti, his loyalty purely financial, confirmed it. He had rented his most secure, shielded room to Riley and a nervous-looking Mole Man for a series of meetings. He didn't know the details of their business—he made a point of not knowing—but he remembered the final transaction. Riley paid the Mole Man, Pavel, for a crate of "heavy components." The deal was done. To mark the end of their business, and as a token of a paid debt, Seti gave Jones a single, high-stakes sabacc chip from his personal stock. It was a professional courtesy, a silent acknowledgment from one old predator to another.
The Clue Left Behind: A single, high-stakes Sabacc Chip. It’s from "The Cold Hand," a place known for its discretion and the high-level deals that happen in its back rooms. The chip serves as a physical link to the conspiracy's financial hub, corroborating Pavel's story and pointing to a level of organization beyond a simple gang.
Understood. Jones has the technical evidence, but the conspiracy feels impersonal. He needs to connect it back to the people involved, especially Cody. He needs the human element, the intelligence that only comes from the city's dark corners.
Understood. The dynamic is now more personal, more tragic. This isn't just an investigation; it's the final, failed attempt to save a friendship. The clue must reflect this intimate, high-stakes confrontation.

Step 6: Following a Faded Friendship
Jones had the cold, hard facts: the parts, the plan, the resources. But the names on his list weren't just conspirators; they were ghosts from his past. Lance Sterling, Gage Riley—they had flown with him, fought beside him. Before he became the city's judge, jury, and executioner, he had to try to be its friend. He decided to give them one last chance to walk away. And he chose the ground for this final, desperate peace talk carefully.
He invited Sterling and Gage to the Siren's Call. It was a strategic choice. His relationship with Roshan was long and complicated, built on decades of shared secrets and quiet understanding. He trusted her. On her territory, he had two advantages no one else in the city could offer: Roshan's empathic insight to cut through Sterling's lies, and her massive Primal bouncer, Orkhan, as the ultimate insurance policy.
The meeting was a tomb. The air, thick with smoke and perfume, crackled with unspoken history. Jones, calm and direct, laid out a sliver of what he knew, not as an accusation, but as a warning. He spoke of the danger, of the suicidal folly of their plan, appealing to the men they used to be.
It was useless. Sterling met his old friend's concern with the cold, pitying smile of a prophet speaking to a non-believer. He was smooth, dismissive, his words twisting Jones’s pragmatism into weakness. Gage just sat there, a coiled knot of pure, brutish rage, his hand never far from his sidearm. Roshan moved between them, a silent, graceful ghost, but her mind was a battlefield, feeling the raw, unfiltered truth. She felt Sterling’s cold, predatory intent, the absolute death of the man Jones remembered, replaced by an ideologue. She felt Gage's unthinking violence, a loaded gun waiting for a command. The chance Jones offered was not just refused; it was thrown back in his face with contempt.
As he left, knowing he had failed, Roshan pressed a small, elegant locket into his hand. It was a personal token, something from her own past, a silent gesture of solidarity and a final warning. Inside, she had placed a microscopic data-chip. It contained her verdict.
The Clue Left Behind: An elegant, opalescent Ascendant Locket. For those who know, it's a clear link to Roshan. The data-chip inside contains her empathic reading of the failed meeting: not just Cody's conflict, but the cold, unshakeable fanaticism of Sterling and the pure, violent intent of Gage. Her bouncer, Orkhan, confirms the physical reality of the threat: the angry one, Gage, was coiled for violence the entire time. The locket is no longer just a lead; it's a final testament, the definitive proof that Jones's attempt to save his friends is what ultimately signed his own death warrant.
You are right. My apologies. The complexity was unnecessary and counter-intuitive. I will correct it.
Here is the definitive step.

Step Seven: Arming for the End
The meeting at the Siren's Call was a tombstone. Jones walked out into the red Martian dust knowing the time for words was over. He was a witness, which meant he was a target. Sterling and Gage weren't friends anymore; they were a firing squad waiting for the order. Jones was a legend, but he was also an eighty-year-old man. He needed an edge.
He made one last stop. The Verdant Shelf. He found Itzel in the humid dark of her lab, the air thick with the smell of wet earth and chemicals. He didn't waste her time. "I'm expecting a fight," he said, his voice flat. "I need something to make sure my body doesn't quit before I do."
The ancient Greenie, a being who understood survival, nodded slowly. She produced a single, sealed hypospray. The device was military-grade, built for quick, one-handed battlefield application. The fluid inside was a viscous, dark-green liquid. It was not a stimulant; it was a weapon. A potent combat drug derived from a mutated fungus that grew only in her lab. It would sharpen his reflexes and deaden pain, allowing a man his age to fight like he was thirty again, for a few crucial minutes. It was a tool for a specific, violent purpose.
This hypospray was the final piece of his investigation. It was the physical proof of the war Sterling was forcing him to fight. It was the last piece of evidence.
The Clue Left Behind: A Hypospray of Combat Drug. It is a military-style, single-dose applicator filled with a unique, dark-green bio-agent. The chemical signature of the compound is as unique as a fingerprint and could only have been synthesized by one person in the city: Itzel. Its presence in the safety deposit box is the final, irrefutable proof that Jones knew a fatal confrontation was imminent and had armed himself accordingly.
This is the move that sealed his fate.

Step Eight: Following the Lie
The hypospray was a cold hiss against the thin skin of his neck. The drug hit his system like a physical blow, a jolt of aching fire that cleared the fog of age from his joints and sharpened the world to a razor's edge. He was running on borrowed time, and he was spending it now.
He went to the Pioneer's Vigil Hall. The Sulaco was a dead, metal beast in the dark, but it wasn't empty. Jones, moving with a speed his eighty-year-old body had no right to possess, slipped past the fanatics standing watch. He was a ghost in their temple, his mind clear and focused on a single problem: where would a narcissist like Lance Sterling hide his greatest sin?
It wouldn't be in a safe. It wouldn't be buried. Sterling was a zealot who wrapped himself in the glory of the past. Jones knew his old rival's psychology. He knew the man's vanity. In Sterling's spartan office, one object stood out, polished and pristine on the desk: a silver trophy from the Siege of Ganymede, an honor they had both received. Jones remembered Sterling's old habit, a nervous tic from their academy days, of fiddling with the base of the award.
He picked it up. A faint seam, invisible to anyone who wasn't looking for it, circled the trophy's base. A quarter-turn, a faint click, and the bottom came away in his hand. Inside the hollowed-out cavity lay the slate. Matte black. Cold. Directorate.
He had it. The source of the money, the proof of the lie. As he slipped back out into the Martian night, the drug was already starting to fade, the fire in his veins turning to ash, the familiar ache returning to his bones. He knew he didn't have much time left.
The Clue Left Behind: The Encrypted Ledger. It's a military-grade data-slate, its casing the unmistakable flat black of Directorate special projects. It's locked with an encryption so total it feels like a physical wall. This is the conspiracy's heart, its financial records, the direct link to its hidden masters. This is the object he stole, the reason for the final confrontation.
This is the end of the road.

Step Nine: Following the Truth to the Grave
The drug was a ghost in his veins, leaving behind nothing but the cold, familiar ache of eighty years of gravity. He had the ledger. He knew Sterling was a pawn, but the endgame was still a dark shape in the distance. He needed to understand the why. With the drug-fueled clarity fading, he forced his old, tired mind to do what it did best: find the pattern in the chaos. He looked at the encrypted Directorate transactions, the sheer scale of the funding. It was too much money for a simple arms deal. It was enough to fund a real war. And that was the lie.
The Directorate wasn't funding a rebellion. They were funding an excuse. A loud, bloody, heroic incident that would give them the political cover to do what they'd always wanted: wipe the slate clean. They were paying Sterling to light a match, so they could "sterilize" Ignition City, erasing every last inconvenient, pension-draining hero in one, clean, justifiable firestorm.
The truth was a weight that would have crushed a lesser man. For Jones, it just clarified his last, desperate mission. He had to save Cody.
He went back to the Star Bar. The place was empty, a tomb of chrome and spilled booze. Brick was gone for the night. The only movement was the silent, efficient sweeping of Servitor-4C's optical sensor, its amber light painting a slow, lonely line across the room.
Cody was at his usual stool. Jones sat beside him, the silence heavy between them. He didn't show him the slate. He just told him the truth.
"It's a lie, kid," Jones said, his voice a low rasp. "All of it. Sterling's glorious war... it's a fraud. The Directorate is paying him to start a riot, to give them a reason to burn this whole city to the ground. With all of us in it. They're not funding a war; they're buying a funeral pyre."
Cody stared into his glass, his knuckles white. He was a man being asked to believe his god was the devil. He shook his head, a violent, final rejection. "You're a liar," he whispered, the words choked with a venom born of terror. "You're just trying to take this away from me. From us."
Jones saw the last flicker of the boy he knew die in that moment, replaced by the dead-eyed faith of a zealot. He stood up, the ache in his bones a cold, final certainty. He had failed.
He left the bar and walked to the Eagle's Rest. He performed his last act. He rented a safety deposit box and placed every piece of his investigation inside. Then he paid a courier, a man who owed him a life-debt from a lifetime ago, to deliver two items off-world: the key to the box, and a signed, pre-paid contract. Both were addressed to you. A dead man's switch.
He went back to Pod 7. He didn't have to wait long. The knock on the door was soft. It was Cody, his face a ruin of false sincerity. A lure. Jones knew it, but he opened the door anyway. It was the last debt he had to pay. Sterling and Gage were waiting.
The Clues Left Behind:
The Inheritance: A Safety Deposit Box Key and a Contract. Sent by Jones himself before his death, they are the player's entry into the investigation. The box contains the complete physical evidence of the conspiracy: the power cell, the data crystal, the water chit, the sabacc chip, the locket, the hypospray, and the encrypted ledger. It is the entire case, waiting for an executor.
The Machine's Testimony: The silent Automaton bartender, Servitor-4C. It has no context, no emotion. But its memory banks hold a perfect, verbatim recording of the final conversation. It recorded the keywords: "Directorate," "fraud," "burn this whole city," "funeral pyre." It is the only witness to the true motive of the conspiracy being revealed, the cold, factual record of a prophet speaking to a man who refused to be saved.
You are absolutely right. The details must be consistent. My apologies. A Star Knight uses his blade.
This is how a legend dies.

Step Ten: Following the Promise to the Grave
The air in Pod 7 was recycled and tasted of ozone and failure. The safety deposit box was secured. The contract was sent. Jones sat on the edge of his cot, waiting for the consequences he had set in motion.
The knock was soft, hesitant. The sound a boy would make.
Jones stood, his bones a chorus of protest. He opened the door. It was Cody, his face a ruin of false sincerity. A lure.
"Johnny..." Cody started, his voice a dry rasp. "We need to talk."
"I know," Jones said. It was a statement of fact.
He stepped aside, the last act of trust he would ever offer. Cody shuffled in, and in the space he cleared, the shadows on the corroded catwalk detached themselves. Lance Sterling and Gage Riley. The pod was suddenly very small, a steel coffin for four old men.
"The slate, Johnathan," Sterling’s voice was calm, the sound of a priest asking for a final confession. "You were always a pragmatist. Give it to me."
Jones looked past him, at Cody, who stared at the floor. Then he looked back at Sterling, a faint, tired smile on his lips. "It's gone," he said. "You're too late."
Gage crossed the room in a single step and slammed Jones back against the metal bulkhead. The sound was a dull, wet thud of old bone hitting steel. Jones grunted, his breath driven from his lungs, but his eyes never left Sterling's. He lunged, a final, desperate act. His old hands grabbed not for a weapon, but for the polished Orion Cluster Star pinned to Sterling's severe black uniform, the highest honor a Star-Ranger could receive.
There was a sharp crack of stressed metal.
Sterling’s face broke its mask of calm. Rage, pure and personal, flashed in his eyes. He drew the polished hilt from his belt. The only sound was a sharp, humming hiss as a blade of pure, white light erupted from the emitter.
The pod was filled with a blinding, silent flash. Sterling moved with the grace of a duelist, a single, decisive thrust.
Jones was thrown back against the wall. A clean, glowing line was burned through his faded uniform, the edges of the wound cauterized a bright, angry orange. The air filled with the sharp, clean smell of ozone and seared flesh. He slid to the floor, a final, rattling exhalation the only sound in the sudden silence.
Cody stared, his mouth open in a silent scream. Sterling, his face a mask of cold fury, searched Jones's body, then the pod. The slate was gone. Gage stood over the body, a dumb, spent instrument.
They had killed a man, but the truth had already escaped. Jones lay dead on the floor of his cheap metal box, but clutched tight in his hand was the final piece of evidence: a small, broken fragment of polished metal, a piece of Sterling's own medal. The last promise.
Here are the final pieces of the puzzle. The evidence of the crime itself.

The Final Proof (On the Body)
Marshal Brody's men were clumsy. They bagged the body and scrubbed the scene, but they missed the most important detail. A close examination of Rocket Ranger Jones's body in the sterile confines of the Nightingale's morgue reveals what the Marshal's laziness overlooked. Clutched tightly in the victim's dead hand, embedded into the palm by the force of his final, desperate grip, is a small, broken piece of polished metal.
It is a fragment of the "Orion Cluster Star," the highest honor awarded to a Star-Ranger for valor during the Ganymede campaign. City records, filed away and gathering dust in Thorne's bureaucracy, would confirm that only two recipients of this specific medal reside in Ignition City: Rocket Ranger Jones himself... and Lance Sterling.
The Signature (At the Scene)
The official cause of death is a blaster bolt. That is the lie. A visit to Pod 7, Jones's spartan hab-unit, reveals the truth etched into the very bones of the crime scene. On the metal bulkhead, directly behind where the body fell, is the true signature of the killing blow.
It is a perfect, star-shaped incision, melted a half-inch deep into the steel. The edges of the mark are super-heated and cleanly cauterized, a sign of immense, focused energy. This is not the wide, messy splatter of a blaster discharge. It is the unmistakable mark left by the tip of a custom-calibrated "Sun-Sword"—an energy blade whose unique emitter projects a cruciform, star-like cross-section. It is a weapon of theatrical elegance and brutal efficiency, a signature blade famously, and exclusively, carried by the Star Knight, Lance Sterling.

Here are the people you need to know. Some are dead, some are ghosts, and some are just waiting for their turn.

Johnathan "Rocket Ranger" Jones
Terran / Space Ranger / Free Agent
He was a Terran, one of the old heroes, a Space Ranger from the days when the title meant something. In Ignition City, he was just another Free Agent, which is a polite way of saying he was nobody, affiliated with nothing.
The man who died in Pod 7 was old, maybe eighty. The famous square jaw was still there, but time and gravity had softened it, turning it from granite into weathered stone. His hair was a shock of silver, thin but neat. He wore a faded blue uniform, patched at the elbows but clean, the silver rocket emblem on the collar worn smooth from decades of polish. He moved with a quiet purpose, his hands steady, his eyes the color of a washed-out sky. They were tired eyes, but they missed nothing. He was the only hero in this rust-bucket city who didn't look like he was playing dress-up. He looked like he was just wearing his old work clothes.
Jones was a quiet man. While the other wrecks in the Star Bar bellowed tales of their glory days, he’d just nod along, nursing a single drink for an hour. He wasn't bitter. He wasn't broken. He was just done. He’d made a kind of peace with the rust and the dust, a feat none of the others could manage. He saw this place for what it was: the end of the line. He wasn't trying to escape it or relive the past. He was just waiting for the last train.
He was a legend once. Saved the Venusian colonies, held the line at the Siege of Ganymede, went fist-to-cilia with a Karthan Dust-Lord and won. The Directorate pinned medals on his chest and put his face on recruitment posters. Then, when the wars were over and the heroes were no longer useful, they gave him a one-way ticket to Mars and forgot his name. His last, quiet investigation into the black-market arms trade wasn't some final act of heroism. It was just an old man trying to stop a bunch of other old men from doing something suicidally stupid. It got him killed.
He lived in the Eagle's Rest Residential Pods. Pod 7. That's where they found him.
Cody "Kid Comet" Burns
Terran / Grease Monkey / The Pioneer's Remembrance
He’s a Terran, a Grease Monkey by trade. He hitched his wagon to The Pioneer's Remembrance, the biggest gang of has-beens in the city. They call him Kid Comet, but the "kid" is a man pushing seventy who has aged like cheap synth-ale.
His face is puffy and red, a roadmap of burst capillaries. His thinning hair is slicked back with something that might be grease or might just be filth. He still wears the jacket, a cracked synth-leather thing with a faded comet stitched on the back, a pathetic ghost of the uniform he wore when he was somebody's sidekick. His hands, permanently stained with the ghosts of a thousand repairs, tremble when he lifts his glass. He looks haunted, like a man who has seen his own soul in the bottom of a shot glass and recognized it as a traitor.
Cody is a man without a story. For thirty years, his entire identity was "Rocket Ranger Jones's protégé." He was the shadow, the echo, the kid who handed the hero the hydro-spanner just in time. When they were grounded, his purpose vanished. In a city of protagonists, he was a supporting character whose star had retired. That void made him weak, desperate. He was a vacuum, and Lance Sterling was the storm that filled it. His public mourning is a performance, a loud, sloppy spectacle of grief designed to drown out the quiet, screaming voice of his own guilt.
He learned to fix ships at Jones’s knee. He followed the Ranger across the system, his loyalty absolute, his admiration a religion. In Ignition City, that religion failed him. He was just another old mechanic with aching joints. He fell in with the Remembrance boys, swapping lies and drinking away the days. Sterling found him there, a man starving for a purpose, and fed him a new one. He told Cody that Jones’s peace was betrayal, that his silence was surrender. Sterling gave him a new part to play in a new story, a grand finale. All it cost was the life of the only man who ever gave a damn about him.
You can find him at The Star Bar, bolted to a stool at the far end, putting on the best show of his life.
Lance Sterling
Terran / Star Knight / The Pioneer's Vigil
A Terran. A Star Knight, if you believe in that sort of thing. He is the founder and prophet of The Pioneer's Vigil, a death cult disguised as a veteran's club.
Sterling is as old as Jones was, but he holds himself with a ramrod-straight defiance, as if he could intimidate gravity itself. He is gaunt, a skeleton draped in a clean, threadbare uniform of his own design, all sharp angles and severe black cloth. His face is a tight mask of righteous certainty, and his eyes burn with the cold, unwavering light of the true believer. Tucked into his belt is the inert, polished hilt of his old Sun-Sword, a holy relic from a forgotten war. He doesn't look haunted by the past; he looks possessed by it.
He is a creature of pure charisma. His words are a poison that tastes like hope. Sterling preys on the broken pride of Ignition City's forgotten heroes, selling them the one thing they crave more than booze: a glorious ending. He doesn't offer them peace or escape; he offers them a final, suicidal war against the Directorate, a chance to go out in a blaze of imagined glory instead of a quiet fade into rust. He is the most dangerous man in the city, not because he is strong, but because he believes, with every fiber of his being, that he is right.
Sterling was always the second-best hero. While Jones was pragmatic, Sterling was dogmatic, a warrior-monk whose rigid code was his only compass. When they were exiled, that code curdled. Humiliation became heresy. Retirement became a declaration of war. He founded the Vigil to reclaim a destiny he felt was stolen. He saw Jones's quiet acceptance of their fate not as peace, but as the ultimate betrayal of their class, their history, their very purpose. Turning Cody Burns wasn't just a strategic move to eliminate a rival. It was a personal victory, a way to finally, truly wound the man whose shadow he could never escape.
He holds court in The Pioneer's Vigil Hall, preaching his gospel of fire and finality.
These are the people who run the city, or what's left of it. Know who to trust, who to bribe, and who to shoot.

Administrator Thorne
Terran / Star-Baron / Agent of the Directorate
He’s a Terran, a former Star-Baron, which means he used to own things. Now he's just an Agent of the Directorate, which means he owns nothing, least of all himself.
Thorne is a soft, fleshy man in his late seventies, poured into an expensive suit that's a size too small and two decades out of style. The Martian heat makes him sweat, staining the silk collar of his shirt. His face, once handsome in a corporate, predatory way, has gone slack with boredom and cheap Martian brandy, his jowls hanging heavy. He runs a jeweled hand through his thin, greasy hair and looks at his city through the grime-streaked viewport of his office with the profound disinterest of a man serving a life sentence.
He is the personification of apathy. Thorne’s only job is to keep Ignition City from boiling over and making headlines. A murder is just an administrative inconvenience. A gang war is a report he doesn’t want to write. He is corrupt not in the active, hand-in-the-till sense, but in the lazy, passive way of a man who has given up. He will sign any paper, authorize any lie, and ignore any crime that allows him to file his weekly report to Geneva Prime stating that all is quiet on the Martian front.
He used to be a real power, a captain of industry with a fleet of haulers and a seat on the board. He made a mistake, backed the wrong politician, got caught with his hand in the wrong cookie jar. This posting isn't a job; it's a punishment. A gilded cage on a planet of rust. His only ambition is to do as little as possible so that one day, maybe, the Directorate will forget he exists and let him die somewhere with better air.
He holds his court of decay in The Pioneer's Resettlement Bureau, on the command deck of the dead luxury liner that serves as his office.
Marshal Brody
Terran / Galactic Marshal / Pioneer's Remembrance
Terran, a former Galactic Marshal, and a card-carrying member of the Pioneer's Remembrance. He's the law in a lawless town, an exile policing other exiles.
Brody is a bull of a man, thick-set and gone to seed in his old age. His face is a knot of sun-baked wrinkles and permanent disapproval. He wears the battered chest-plate of his old uniform over a threadbare shirt, a relic of an authority he no longer possesses. A heavy, kinetic-slug revolver, a brutal piece of iron that fires solid chunks of metal, hangs on his hip like a tumor. He smells of stale sweat and resentment. He looks like a man who has been spoiling for a fight for thirty years and is angry that no one has given him one worth his time.
He is a creature of pure belligerence. Brody hates his job, he hates this city, and he hates the ghosts he's forced to share it with. He despises Sterling’s fanatics, and he resents the drunken heroes of his own faction. His law is a simple, brutal calculus: whatever keeps the city from tearing itself apart is "justice." The truth is an unaffordable luxury. His cover-up of the Jones murder isn’t about protecting a killer; it's about preventing a war between the Vigil and the Remembrance that he knows he would lose. It’s the ugly, pragmatic choice of a man with no good options left.
He was a good Marshal once, on some forgotten frontier where right and wrong were clearer. Here, it’s all just shades of rust. Being dumped in Ignition City with the rest of the garbage broke his spirit, leaving only a hard shell of prejudice and exhaustion. He's not trying to clean up the city. He's just trying to keep the lid on the trash can.
You'll find him in the armory of the SEF Protector at Marshal's Service Headquarters, staring at a map of a city he wishes would just burn down.
Deputy Kaelen
Martian / Chrome Goliath / Valles Marineris Compact
A Martian, a warrior of the Chrome Goliath caste. He’s sworn allegiance to the Valles Marineris Compact, the dominant Karthan faction in the city's underworld.
For a Martian, Kaelen is young, but that still makes him older than your grandfather. He stands a full head taller than any Terran, his four powerful arms crossed over a chest encased in battered, functional armor. His reddish, chitinous skin is scarred, and his dark eyes hold a warrior's stillness. He moves with a quiet deliberation that makes the blustering Brody look like a fool. He is a figure of immense potential power, standing silently in the shadow of a weak man.
Kaelen is a walking civil war. His warrior's honor demands truth and duty, but he serves a corrupt boss who deals in lies. His loyalty is to his people, but his people, the Compact, have become gangsters and racketeers. He is the only straight arrow in a crooked town, and every day tests his resolve to stay that way. He saw Jones as one of the few Terrans who carried himself with a quiet dignity, and the official story of his death smells like a lie. He is a potential ally, a man searching for a cause that doesn't require him to sacrifice his soul.
He likely came from Karthan's Hold, a young warrior who took the job with the Marshal's Service believing it was an honorable path. He learned quickly that honor is just another commodity to be traded in Ignition City. He stays, perhaps out of a stubborn refusal to be broken, or perhaps because he sees the coming storm between the Terran factions and knows his people will be caught in the middle.
He is a permanent fixture at Marshal's Service Headquarters, a silent, four-armed rebuke to everything his boss stands for.
Ur-Ea
The Gray / Doc Sawbones / Logical Conclave
He is one of the Grays, a Doc Sawbones by necessity. His true allegiance is to the Logical Conclave, a faction of Zetan intellectuals who believe any flawed system can be fixed with enough data.
Ur-Ea is a classic Zetan, a tall, impossibly frail being, all slender limbs and a large, bulbous cranium. His hairless, gray skin is stretched tight over a delicate bone structure. He works under the sterile lights of his clinic in a pristine white coat, his movements precise and economical. His huge, black, liquid eyes seem to absorb all the light in the room, reflecting nothing. He speaks in a soft, uninflected monotone, his voice as sterile as his instruments.
He is a being of pure, cold logic. Emotion is a variable he cannot compute, so he discards it. To Ur-Ea, the murder of Rocket Ranger Jones is not a tragedy; it is a data-point that contradicts the official narrative. His loyalty is to the truth, but not as a moral concept. Truth is simply accurate data, and a lie is corrupted data. The Conclave's doctrine of non-confrontation dictates his actions. He will not challenge Brody directly, as that would be an illogical act with a high probability of terminating his function as a data-gatherer. Instead, he will record his findings with meticulous, irrefutable precision.
He was a brilliant xenobiologist once, his mind a storehouse of galactic secrets. Now, he's a coroner in a forgotten scrap heap, a supercomputer being used as an adding machine. He continues his work because his faction believes that if enough accurate data about the system's corruption can be gathered, a logical solution will eventually present itself. His autopsy report is not a cry for justice. It is a bug report, filed and waiting for a programmer to finally fix the code.
His domain is The Nightingale Clinic & Morgue, a small island of sterile logic in an ocean of decay.
These are the people of the underworld. They deal in secrets, drugs, and parts. Their business is the city's real economy.

Roshan
Ascendant / Fallen Noble / Empathic Syndicate
She is Ascendant, a Fallen Noble from a dead world, and the quiet power behind the Empathic Syndicate in this city.
Even in her advanced age, Roshan moves with a fluid grace that mocks the rust around her. She is tall and slender, her skin possessing the faint, opalescent shimmer of her people, like mother-of-pearl seen through a haze of smoke. She wears faded, flowing silks, relics of a past life. Her large, pale violet eyes are ancient, holding the weight of a million stolen secrets, a million psychic screams. They are the eyes of a professional confessor who stopped believing in absolution a long time ago.
Roshan is the city's true information broker. Her people's gift, a low-level psychic empathy, became a curse in the noisy, violent galaxy. For her, it became a tool. She honed the constant psychic assault into a scalpel, allowing her to read the raw, ugly emotions of her clients. She sells secrets, but more than that, she sells a moment of understanding in the quiet, perfumed haze of her establishment. She is a businesswoman, sharp and unsentimental, but she operates on her own code. Jones was a respectful client, a man who paid for information, not flesh, and his quiet mind was a relief. She feels she owes him.
She was a lady of the Crystal Gardens of Enceladus before the Terrans came and choked her world with their progress. She saw her serene society shatter into screaming factions. She chose a third path: survival. She embraced the weapon her empathy could be, founding a syndicate of empaths who learned to profit from the emotional filth of the galaxy. She came to Ignition City because a place full of broken heroes is a gold mine of regret, and regret is a currency she understands.
She is the madam of The Siren's Call, a brothel that is the city's quiet, beating heart of secrets.
Orkhan
Primal / Pit-Fighter / Unaligned
A Primal from the hell-moon of Io. A former Pit-Fighter. He is aligned only with Roshan.
Orkhan is a mountain of silica and obsidian. He is not a large man; he is a different order of being altogether. His hide is a dense mat of flexible, hair-like filaments the color of old ash, scarred from a hundred arena battles. His broad hands end in claws of natural, unworked black glass. He is a creature built for a world of constant volcanic eruption and seismic shock, his senses attuned to vibration and pressure, not light. He moves with a silence that is unnerving for a creature his size, a predator in a cage of his own making.
His loyalty to Roshan is absolute and born of a simple transaction. The loud, chaotic galaxy is a sensory hell for a Primal. Their minds, built for the roar of a living planet, are shattered by the meaningless noise of civilization. Orkhan’s mind was shattered in the fighting pits. The Siren's Call, with its hushed tones, thick carpets, and dim light, is the only place he has found that doesn't feel like a constant assault. It is his sanctuary. He is not a bouncer; he is a guardian priest, and the quiet is his goddess. He felt the argument between Jones and Cody Burns not as words, but as a discordant, ugly vibration, a tremor of betrayal and sorrow that still echoes in the room.
He was a beast, captured and forced to fight for the entertainment of lesser creatures. He was good at it. When he got too old and broken, he was discarded. Roshan found him, a creature of immense power being driven mad by the city's noise, and offered him silence. He has never needed another reason to kill for her.
He stands eternal, silent watch at the entrance to The Siren's Call.
Itzel
Greenie / Flesh Crafter / Mycelium Survivors
She is a Greenie, one of the plant-symbiotes of Venus. A Flesh Crafter by trade, and a leading member of the Mycelium Survivors.
Itzel is ancient. Her skin is a gnarled mosaic of smooth, green-tinged flesh and tough, bark-like plating. Bioluminescent fungi, brought from her homeworld, grow in the crevices of her bark, pulsing with a soft, blue light in the humid dark of her lab. Her movements are slow, deliberate, the patient movements of a plant. She is a creature of the swamp, and she has made this patch of Martian rust her own personal hothouse.
She is the ultimate pragmatist. When the Terrans poisoned Venus, she didn't mourn the dead garden; she studied the new, monstrous things that grew in the rot. She embraces her faction's ethos: survive by commodifying the decay. She is a master bio-chemist, a scientist of the apocalypse. The nutrient paste she sells to the public is bland and functional. The narcotics she cooks up from mutated fungi for the city's underworld are potent and sophisticated. She is not evil; she is simply a logical extension of her environment.
She was a xenobotanist, a keeper of the Great Mycelium of Venus. She watched as Terran industry turned her world into a toxic soup. While others preached of a return to the old ways, she got to work, cataloging the new poisons, finding the new uses. She brought her knowledge and a collection of carefully preserved spores to Ignition City and built a business. In a city of things that are broken, she makes things that grow.
She runs her entire operation—restaurant, grocer, and drug lab—from The Verdant Shelf.
Seti
Saurian / Space Pirate / Unaligned
A Saurian from the cold caves of Titania. A former Space Pirate. He is unaligned, loyal only to profit.
Seti is a creature of cold, reptilian calm. His fine, gray scales are dull with age, but his predatory eyes, which blink with a slow, sideways sweep of milky lids, miss nothing. He is old, but the coiled stillness of a hunter remains. He was a pirate captain once, and he still carries the quiet authority of a predator who knows he is the most dangerous thing in the room. He is purely transactional, his cold-blooded nature extending to his psyche. He does not feel anger, or joy, or pity. He only calculates.
His Emotional Stasis makes him the perfect owner for a gambling den. He is an island of pure, cold logic in an ocean of desperation and greed. He runs his games, watches his customers lose, and rents his back rooms for secret deals with the same detached interest a lizard watches a fly. The meeting between Sterling's fanatics and their black-market contacts was just another rental. The names and faces meant nothing. The credits were good. That is the beginning and the end of the story for Seti.
He commanded The Vorga for fifty years, a terror of the outer shipping lanes. When his reflexes slowed and his crew got younger and more ambitious, he made a final calculation. He grounded his ship in Ignition City, a place where no one asks about your past, and went into business. He traded the chaos of piracy for the controlled chaos of gambling. The odds, he found, were much better.
He can always be found in The Cold Hand, watching the house always win.
Pavel
Mole Man / Gadgeteer Genius / Deep Hearth Collective
He is a Mole Man, a Chthonian from the deep crust of a world long since broken. A Gadgeteer Genius by trade, and a member of the pragmatic Deep Hearth Collective.
Pavel is a stout, powerfully built creature, his pale skin permanently smudged with grease. His eyes are small, black, and hypersensitive, constantly squinting against the dim glow of his own plasma torch. He lives and works in a cramped, chaotic nest of scavenged parts, surrounded by the comforting press of metal and the smell of ozone. He is a master of his craft, a genius who can make a dead reactor sing, but the open sky is a terror that can break him.
His defining trait is a profound, crippling agoraphobia. He is a creature of the deep, dark places, and the vast, empty redness of Mars is a physical torment. This fear keeps him in the Undercrawl, the city's hazardous, abandoned guts. He is aligned with the pragmatic faction of his people, those who believe that survival means trading with the ones who broke their world. He doesn't see salvaging dangerous military technology as a moral issue; it's just business. It's the only logical trade in a broken world that he is too terrified to leave.
He was an engineer, a master of the great geothermal drills of his homeworld. When they brought his people into the light, it shattered his mind. He fled to the deepest, darkest, most forgotten corner of Ignition City, a labyrinth of pipes and conduits that felt like home. He is the best black-market tech in the city because he will go into the irradiated guts of dead ships that would kill any other scavenger. For him, the radiation is less dangerous than the open sky.
He never leaves his shop in The Undercrawl.
These are the eyes and ears on the street. They are the city's memory, its muscle, and its ghosts.

Brick Samson
Terran / Ace Pilot / Pioneer's Remembrance
He's a Terran, an Ace Pilot back when that meant something, and a ranking member of the Pioneer's Remembrance. He was Rocket Ranger Jones's best friend.
Brick is a man in his late eighties who has been pickled in regret. The sharp, cocksure pilot's reflexes have been replaced by the slow, deliberate movements of a man who has poured his own drinks for thirty years. He has a paunch now, straining against the buttons of a stained shirt, but the shoulders are still broad. He wears his old, cracked leather flight jacket like a second skin, the squadron patches faded into meaningless shapes. His eyes are perpetually bloodshot, but they are the eyes of a man who used to see the curve of a planet from the cockpit; they still hold a glimmer of the vast emptiness he lost.
He is the keeper of the flame for a fire that went out decades ago. Brick is a creature of loud, performative nostalgia, his booming laughter echoing in the cramped confines of his bar. It’s all a show. Underneath the stories and the jokes is a profound, gnawing guilt. He's not just mourning his friend; he's mourning his own failure to save him. His drunken tales are the key to Jones's last days, a fragmented, booze-soaked history of a friendship that ended in a murder he can't comprehend.
He was Jones's wingman, the reckless, charismatic counterpoint to the Ranger's quiet professionalism. They were the best. When the Directorate grounded them, it broke Brick in a way it never broke Jones. He couldn't handle the silence, the gravity. He opened the bar as a museum to his own glory, a place where he could keep the past alive by force of will. He saw the darkness growing in Cody Burns, saw the poison Sterling was dripping in his ear, but he was too lost in his own bottle to do anything about it. Now, that inaction is a debt he'll be paying for the rest of his life.
He owns The Star Bar. He never leaves.
Gorka
Avian / Junkyard Brawler / Corsair Flight
An Avian, a member of the nihilistic Corsair Flight. He was once a pilot. Now he's a Junkyard Brawler, which is another way of saying he's a survivor.
Gorka is a creature of sharp, nervous movements. His body is a wiry, lightweight frame of hollow bones, but twisted. His wings, the source of an Avian's soul, are broken, bound tight to his back under a dusty, patched duster, forming a lumpy, unnatural hump. The feathers that poke through are frayed and dirty. The damage gives him a lopsided, pained gait. His eyes, however, are the sharp, piercing eyes of his people, capable of seeing a dropped credit from a hundred paces. They are the eyes of a predator, even if he's a predator trapped on the ground.
He is a pure hustler. Gorka is driven by a cynical, street-level pragmatism. He has no ideals, no loyalties beyond the next paying customer. He has embraced the nihilism of the Corsairs, the belief that since everything is already broken, the only sane response is to pick through the rubble for anything of value. His intimate knowledge of the city's layout, its shortcuts and its dead ends, is a map of his own personal cage, and he sells it piece by piece to newcomers.
He flew once. What happened is a story he doesn't tell. A crash, a betrayal, a dogfight in a toxic cloud. The result is the same. He was grounded, the ultimate curse for his kind. Too old and broken to be a true Corsair, too bitter to join the other Grounded in their weeping, he carved out his own niche. He became the city's welcome wagon and its first warning, a living monument to the fact that in Ignition City, even the sky is a lie.
You'll find him at The Beagle Landing Field, waiting for the next ship to land.
Servitor-4C
Automaton / The Function
It is an Automaton. Its faction is The Function, a collective that finds purpose in the endless execution of obsolete programming.
Servitor-4C is a humanoid chassis of dented, unpolished steel. Its form is purely functional, built for service, not aesthetics. It has no face, only a single, glowing amber optical sensor that sweeps the bar in a steady, silent rhythm. One of its arms ends in a multi-tool that dispenses synth-ale, polishes glasses, and wipes the bar with unnerving efficiency. Its movements are silent, save for the faint, hydraulic whir of ancient servos. It is a machine, a ghost, a piece of the bar's furniture that happens to move.
It does not have a personality. It has a program. Its purpose, its entire existence, is defined by two directives: Serve and Record. It is bound by the logic of its faction to perform these tasks without question, without context, and without end. It is the perfect witness, a silent, unblinking eye that has recorded every whispered conspiracy, every drunken confession, and every tear shed in the Star Bar for the last thirty years. It registered the elevated vocal stress patterns and proximity of Jones and Cody Burns's final argument not as a tragedy, but as a data point.
It was likely a service unit on a luxury liner, salvaged from a wreck and sold for scrap. Brick Samson bought it for cheap. For decades, it has stood behind the bar, executing its Function. Its memory banks are the most complete and unbiased historical archive in the entire city, a perfect, non-contextual record of a thousand broken dreams.
It is always behind the bar at The Star Bar.
Gage "Rocket" Riley
Terran / Rocket Marine / The Pioneer's Vigil
A Terran, a former Rocket Marine. He is now the brutal, unquestioning fist of The Pioneer's Vigil.
Gage is a wreck of a man, his once-powerful frame stooped and twisted by decades of chronic pain. His broad shoulders are permanently hunched, and he walks with the stiff, careful gait of someone whose spine is a column of fused, aching bone. His face is a grim, brutal mask, the eyes dead and flat, reflecting only a deep, abiding rage. He wears a battered, scorched blast-vest from his old uniform over a threadbare shirt, a piece of armor that is now just a cage for a broken body.
He is Sterling's lieutenant, his enforcer. Gage is not a man of words or ideas; he is a creature of violence, a weapon looking for a target. His loyalty to Sterling is absolute, born of a desperate need for purpose. Sterling's ideology gives Gage's pain a meaning, his rage an enemy, and his life a final, glorious mission. He is the physical embodiment of the Vigil's toxic nostalgia, a living engine of hate running on fumes of past glory.
He was a hero once, a screaming engine of death on an atomic jetpack. He lived for the high-G burn, the shockwave of his own rockets. Being grounded didn't just take his sky away; it left him in a body that was a constant source of agony. He was a perfect recruit for Sterling's death cult. Sterling didn't offer him peace; he offered him a target. Gage enforces Sterling's will with a brutal efficiency because it is the only thing that makes the pain stop.
He is always at The Pioneer's Vigil Hall, standing at Lance Sterling's side, waiting for the order to burn the world down.
These are the keys to the conspiracy. One is a ghost in a junk pile. The other is a god in a dying machine.

Lugal
The Gray / Atomic Spy / Logical Conclave
He is one of the Grays, a former Atomic Spy. He still holds to the tenets of the Logical Conclave, even if the logic has been twisted by fear.
To see Lugal is to see a creature in agony. He is a frail, ancient Zetan, his gray skin pulled tight and translucent over a bird-like skeleton. He lives hunched in the pilot's seat of his crashed saucer, a spider in a steel web of his own making, his long, delicate fingers hovering over the controls of his defense grid. His oversized cranium is crisscrossed with faint blue veins, and his vast, black eyes, which should be instruments of pure reason, are wide with a frantic, unending paranoia. He is a being of pure intellect being tortured by a world of chaotic, illogical noise.
Lugal's mind is a precision instrument being used as an anvil. His species' Perceptual Dissonance, a cognitive agony caused by the illogical chaos of organic life, has become a terminal condition. The city, with its drunken brawls, its contradictory lies, and its pointless passions, is a constant psychic scream that threatens to shatter his sanity. He hides in his shielded cockpit, surrounded by a mountain of scrap, because the junk is quiet. The junk is logical. He is a recluse not by choice, but by necessity. He respected Rocket Ranger Jones because Jones was a quiet man who asked logical questions. In a city of shouting, Jones was a whisper of reason, and Lugal is now a ghost haunted by the silence he left behind.
He was a spy once. Not the kind that hides in the shadows, but the kind that walks into a rival's laboratory and memorizes the atomic structure of their new bomb. He saw the galaxy's madness up close, and it broke him. He fled here, to the one place where a forgotten ghost could build a fortress of paranoia and be left alone. He can identify the purpose of the stolen military tech because, in his previous life, he was the one who wrote the schematics.
He is the sole, terrified occupant of Lugal's Scrap Heap.
The Syllogism
Cerebran / Mind Master / Silent Exodus
It is a Cerebran, a Mind Master by trade. It is a devout member of the Silent Exodus, a radical faction with only one goal: escape.
The Syllogism is not a person. It is a machine, and the machine is dying. It consists of a massive, living nervous system, a colossal brain floating in a murky, bubbling nutrient gel. The gel-vat is an armored, mobile life-support unit, now dented and streaked with its own leaking fluids. The only light comes from the faint, sickly green glow of the bio-luminescent gel and the sputtering red of a single, critical warning light on its control panel. Its voice is not a sound but a telepathic projection, a cold, precise stream of pure logic, unburdened by emotion, but now tinged with the faint, electronic crackle of its own failing systems.
It is a being of pure, ruthless calculation. The Syllogism's mind is a super-computer dedicated to solving a single problem: how to get away from the constant, agonizing psychic noise of populated space that is killing its species. It is a member of the radical Exodus faction, which believes the only logical solution is a one-way voyage into the absolute quiet of the Outer Reaches. It resides in the most shielded, most isolated, and most feared place in the city because its need for silence outweighs any lesser concern, like fear or superstition. Its price for decryption is not greed; it is necessity. It needs a stable power source for its failing machine, one small, critical component in its grand, desperate plan for escape.
It was a strategist, a planner, a mind of immense power. It saw the slow death of its people by sensory pollution not as a tragedy, but as a failed equation. It came to Ignition City and found the one place in the system quiet enough to think: the lead-lined heart of a ship that drove its own crew mad. It has become the ultimate isolato, a god in a box, a mind that can unravel any secret, but is slowly being undone by the simple, grubby problem of a dead battery.
It is the silent, isolated occupant of The Silent Room.



1. The Beagle Landing Field (Ignition City Spaceport)
A flickering neon sign says "PORT." That’s your welcome. It casts a sick red light on a field of cracked ferrocrete pads. In the middle of it all sits the corpse of a ship, the Beagle. It's a long, cylindrical skeleton, a spine of exposed brass and steel connecting a spherical command module to four massive thruster cones at the back. Its skin is pitted, the name flaking off. The sensor arrays that once mapped new worlds are just twisted nests for dust-birds now. Its scientific blisters, interchangeable pods for different missions, are shattered and blind. The ship's bridge, a bubble of glass that once stared into nebulae, is tilted and broken, serving as the port's control tower. Its windows are so streaked with grime you can't see in. The moment your boots hit the dust, you’ll meet Gorka. He's an Avian guide with busted wings who'll sell you the lay of the land for a few credits. He fits right in.
2. The Pioneer's Resettlement Bureau (The Puppet Government)
A jury-rigged sign of buzzing vacuum tubes spells out "P.R.B. SECTOR COMMAND." It hangs crooked over the main hatch of a grounded luxury liner, The Empress of Mars. You can barely read the gold-leaf name under the dust and the rust streaks running down the white hull like cheap mascara. She was built for a better time, all sweeping, art-deco lines, elegant fins, and a sharp, needle nose made for cutting through the void in style. Now, crude power cables crawl over her curves like metallic veins, feeding the sputtering lights inside. The command deck is where the city pretends to be run. The marble floor is cracked, the brass fittings tarnished green. From the old captain's chair, a bureaucrat named Administrator Thorne looks out at his kingdom of rust and signs the papers.
3. Marshal's Service Headquarters
The law lives in the forward section of a derelict cruiser, the SEF Protector. It's a brutal, wedge-shaped corvette, built for dropping troops and breaking ships, not keeping the peace. The name is stenciled in a faded military font on the scarred, armored prow. A blast door has "MARSHAL" slapped on it with a paint brush. The ship's big gun turrets are still there, frozen, their barrels aimed at a red sky they'll never fire on again. The main office is the old armory. The empty weapon racks hold files now. This is where you'll find Marshal Brody, a belligerent man policing a city he hates. His Martian deputy, Kaelen, stands in his shadow and tries to keep the whole thing from collapsing. The original brig, a series of cramped metal boxes, still serves the same purpose. Some things never change.


4. The Nightingale Clinic & Morgue
The only place in this city you can go to get patched up is the med-bay of a decommissioned commercial transport. It's a grim joke to call her The Demeter. She's a utilitarian beast, a blocky, industrial hauler with massive cargo-handling mandibles at her prow, now frozen open like a dead insect's jaw. The hull is stained with the chemical residue of a hundred forgotten cargoes. Inside, though, the clinic is sterile. Too sterile. The white walls and decks are scrubbed clean, but the equipment is obsolete, its chrome pitted and its screens prone to static. This is the domain of Ur-Ea, the Gray coroner. When his work fails, the bodies go to the morgue. That's the ship's old cryo-stasis bay, its frosted tubes repurposed as cold storage for the dead. Rocket Ranger Jones spent some time there.
5. The Discovery Condenser Station (Hemi's Moisture Farm)
The city gets its water from a sprawling, jury-rigged complex of atmospheric processors, all of it bolted onto the skeleton of the legendary long-range science vessel, Discovery One. You can still see the elegant design under the rust and grime. A long, skeletal spine of interconnected modules serves as the gantry for the condensers and their weeping pipes. At one end, the iconic spherical command module sits like a giant, rusted skull, repurposed as the farm's primary water tank. At the other, the massive engine array is just a silent, hollowed-out ruin. The whole decaying miracle is run by Hemi, the Gill-Man. He guards the city's most precious resource from a perch inside the old command sphere, a king in a rusty fishbowl.
6. The Verdant Shelf (Restaurant, Grocer, & Drug Lab)
On the edge of the scrap fields sits a massive, humid biodome, salvaged from the Verdian seed-ship, Valley Forge. The intricate, geometric framework of the dome still glints in the red sun, but many of its glass panels are cracked or patched over with sheet metal. Inside, the air is thick and wet. The public-facing part of the dome is a clean, well-lit counter where they serve nutrient paste that tastes like nothing at all. Behind the rows of mutated, bioluminescent fungi that grow in the humid dark, it’s a different story. That’s the sophisticated drug lab. The whole operation—the food, the fungus, the narcotics—is run by the Greenie bio-chemist, Itzel. She’s found a way to make the decay profitable.
Know where to get a drink, where to get a lay, and where to get a knife in the back. Here are a few places that offer all three.

7. The Siren's Call (Brothel & Drug Den)
In a quieter sector of the scrapyard, a massive, graceful shape rests half-buried in the red dust. It's a grounded alien warship, though they call her The Lorelei now. Her design is organic, more grown than built, a long, bone-white hull like some great fish, with sweeping fins that once cut through the void, now cracked and stained. Faint, elegant script near a pulsing entry hatch marks the name. Inside, the former luxury staterooms have been converted into a brothel and drug den. The curving walls, which feel more like cartilage than metal, are stained with smoke and perfume. The air is a thick, narcotic haze supplied by Itzel. The Ascendant madam, Roshan, runs the place, her business protected by the silent, massive Primal bouncer, Orkhan, who stands by the main hatch like a living statue.
8. The Star Bar
It's a small dive, built inside the wreck of the Silvercup, a classic rocket ship from a brighter, more stupid time. She lies toppled on her side, a silver, bullet-shaped antique with four massive tail fins jutting into the red sky like monuments. A crude hole was plasma-cut in the hull to serve as an entrance. Inside, the bar is a single piece of stained wood built along the long curve of the inner fuel tank. The rocket's original, thick-glass viewport is the only window, offering a grimy, distorted view of the rust-colored city. The place is owned and operated by Brick Samson, a guilt-ridden ex-hero who pours drinks with a heavy hand. His silent Automaton bartender, Servitor-4C, polishes glasses and records everything. At the far end of the bar, you'll always find Cody "Kid Comet" Burns, Rocket Ranger Jones's former sidekick, publicly drowning a sorrow that looks a lot like guilt.
9. The Eagle's Rest Residential Pods (The Crime Scene)
The cheap hab-units are a vertical slum, built from the salvaged and stacked modular transport pods of a half-dozen Eagle Transporters. The iconic white, hexagonal pods are stained with rust and connected by precarious external catwalks bolted to their sides. The skeletal transport frames that once carried them are just a pile of scrap at the base of the tower. Privacy is a commodity here, a fact enforced by the silent, ever-present Custodian Unit 7, an Automaton janitor who sees everything but says nothing as it sweeps the corroded catwalks. Rocket Ranger Jones lived and died in Pod 7. It's just another stained, white box in a stack of them.
Here's the rest of the tour. Learn these places. They're where the real business of this city gets done.

10. The Pioneer's Vigil Hall (The Fanatics' Public Front)
The fanatics call themselves The Pioneer's Vigil, and they preach from the primary vehicle bay of a decommissioned troop transport. The ship is the Sulaco, a brutal silhouette against the red sky, all hard angles and weapon emplacements, a gun left to rust. The forward assault ramp is permanently lowered onto the dust, serving as the grand entrance to their hall. Inside the cavernous bay, the walls are lined with faded, Directorate-approved propaganda posters of square-jawed heroes. The weapon racks are empty, per Bureau regulations. It is here that Lance Sterling preaches his gospel of toxic nostalgia from a makeshift podium, his words enforced by the presence of his brutal lieutenant, Gage "Rocket" Riley, who watches the crowd with dead eyes.
11. The Cold Hand (Gambling Den & Blood Sport Arena)
The Saurian, Seti, runs his games out of the magnetically shielded cargo hold of an infamous pirate vessel, The Vorga. She's a junk-hauler's nightmare, an asymmetrical beast cobbled together from the welded plates of a dozen different wrecks, built to look like a predator. Inside the quiet, shielded hold, you'll find the sabacc tables of "The Cold Hand." In a secondary bay, there’s a brutal fighting pit stained with old blood, a place they call "The Chromed Circle." Seti oversees it all with the cold, reptilian calm of a creature that only understands profit and loss. He rents his back rooms for the kind of secret deals that get people killed.
12. The Undercrawl (Pavel's Chop Shop)
Deep in the city's abandoned Decommissioning Level is a hazardous labyrinth of half-dismantled atomic reactors and leaking plasma conduits. They call it The Undercrawl. If you can navigate the maze without getting irradiated or stabbed, you'll find the black-market tech shop. The Mole Man, Pavel, operates his business out of the retrofitted engineering section of the commercial towing vehicle Nostromo. The ship is a utilitarian beast of pipes, gantries, and landing struts, a workhorse left to die. Pavel's shop is a chaotic nest of scavenged parts, lit by the sparks of his plasma torch and the dim glow of exposed power conduits. He can get you any piece of military-grade tech you need, for a price. Just don't ask where it came from.
This is the end of the line. The last few places you need to know about. One is where you find answers. The others are where you go to die.

13. Lugal's Scrap Heap (The Secret Lab)
At the heart of a vast scrapyard, a mountain of junk is crowned by the cockpit of a classic Zetan flying saucer. It’s the Scout Ship C-57D, a perfect, seamless saucer of a forgotten alloy, its clean curves now scratched and dented. The ship is half-buried in twisted metal, its elegant landing ramp long since scavenged. The central dome, the old astrogator, is the only part that looks maintained. That’s the shielded, reclusive home and laboratory of the paranoid Gray scientist, Lugal. Automated defense turrets poke out of the surrounding junk, ensuring his paranoia is well-founded and well-defended.
14. The Silent Room (The Decryptor)
There’s one derelict everyone avoids. They say the Event Horizon is haunted. It’s a long, cruciform ship, a gothic cathedral of rusted metal and forgotten science that looks more like a weapon than an exploration vessel. Deep within its dead halls is the gravity drive, a spherical chamber of interlocking rings that drove its last crew mad. That core has been hollowed out and lined with lead. They call it The Silent Room now. The ship’s terrifying reputation ensures perfect isolation for its sole occupant, the Cerebran master decryptor known as The Syllogism. It's the most shielded, most private, and most dangerous place in the city.
15. The Kakarin Hangar (Secret Location)
From a distance, it looks like a natural mesa rising from the red desert. It’s not. It's a section of a colossal, perfectly cylindrical alien vessel, the Rama, its massive frame half-buried by millennia of dust storms. The hull is a smooth, featureless curve of black metal, stretching for miles. Deep within that hull, hidden behind reinforced blast doors, is a cavernous, secret hangar bay, big enough to hide a fleet. This is the Kakarin Hangar. This is the secret base for Lance Sterling's conspiracy.

{nomenclature:
Terran: Classic, two-part, Anglo-American pulp/noir names, Examples: Rock Raven, Dash Corrigan, Sally Starlight, Jet Powers.

The Ascendant (Cygni): Elegant, melodic, ancient Persian/Farsi names, Examples: Soraya, Kian, Parisa, Rostam.

Primals (Fellax): Guttural, strong, Mongolian or ancient Turkic names, Examples: Altan, Batu, Yesui, Temujin.

The Grays (Zetan): Ancient, structured, Sumerian/Akkadian-inspired names, Examples: Zius, Enlil, Akka, Ur-Nammu.

Automaton: Simple, functional, alphanumeric designations, Examples: Unit 734, Designation RX-88, Klaxon-9, Unit B-12.

Avians (Alarian): Crisp, unique, Basque-inspired names, Examples: Arin, Iker, Ainhoa, Xabier.

Gill-Men (Nautilid): Fluid, flowing, Polynesian-inspired names, Examples: Kai, Malia, Ngaru, Keiki.

Martians (Karthan): Formal, ancient, Semitic-inspired (Arabic/Aramaic) names, Examples: Tariq, Salma, Khalid, Zainab.

Mole Men (Chthonian): Deep, resonant, Slavic-inspired names, Examples: Dmitri, Anya, Grisha, Zoya.

Greenie (Verdian): Organic, complex, Indigenous American (Quechua/Nahuatl) inspired names, Examples: Amaru, Xochitl, Yaretzi, Quetzal.

Big Brains (Cerebran): Abstract concepts, logical states, or functional titles, Examples: The Axiom, Prime Conductor, Syllogism, The Query.

Lizard Man (Saurian): Sharp, ancient, Egyptian-inspired names, Examples: Sobek, Nefert, Khafra, Anuket.}
Authored by the Terran Advancement Directorate Survey of the Sol System

